TY  - JOUR
T1  - Changes in Marital Sorting: Theory and Evidence from the United                         States
AU  - Chiappori, Pierre-André
AU  - Costa Dias, Monica
AU  - Meghir, Costas
AU  - Zhang, Hanzhe
Y1  - 2025/05/27
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/736764
DO  - 10.1086/736764
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3045
EP  - 3077
VL  - 133
IS  - 10
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Positive assortative matching refers to the tendency of individuals with similar characteristics to form partnerships. Measuring the extent to which assortative matching differs between two economies is challenging when the marginal distributions of the sorting characteristic (e.g., education) change for either or both sexes. We show how the use of different measures can generate different conclusions. We provide an axiomatic characterization for the odds ratio, normalized trace, and likelihood ratio and provide a structural economic interpretation of the odds ratio. We use our approach to show that marital sorting by education substantially changed between the 1950s and the 1970s cohorts.
AB  - Positive assortative matching refers to the tendency of individuals with similar characteristics to form partnerships. Measuring the extent to which assortative matching differs between two economies is challenging when the marginal distributions of the sorting characteristic (e.g., education) change for either or both sexes. We show how the use of different measures can generate different conclusions. We provide an axiomatic characterization for the odds ratio, normalized trace, and likelihood ratio and provide a structural economic interpretation of the odds ratio. We use our approach to show that marital sorting by education substantially changed between the 1950s and the 1970s cohorts.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/736764
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/736764
Y2  - 2026/04/24
