TY  - JOUR
T1  - Persuaded Search
AU  - Mekonnen, Teddy
AU  - Murra-Anton, Zeky
AU  - Pakzad-Hurson, Bobak
Y1  - 2025/05/27
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/736765
DO  - 10.1086/736765
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3167
EP  - 3207
VL  - 133
IS  - 10
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We consider sequential search by an agent who cannot observe the quality of goods but can acquire information from a profit-maximizing principal with limited commitment power. The principal can charge higher prices for more informative signals, but high future prices discourage continued search, thereby reducing the principal?s profits. A unique stationary equilibrium outcome exists: the principal (i) sells the agent only partial information, (ii) induces the socially efficient stopping rule, and (iii) extracts the full surplus. However, introducing an additional, free source of information can lead to inefficiency in equilibrium.
AB  - We consider sequential search by an agent who cannot observe the quality of goods but can acquire information from a profit-maximizing principal with limited commitment power. The principal can charge higher prices for more informative signals, but high future prices discourage continued search, thereby reducing the principal?s profits. A unique stationary equilibrium outcome exists: the principal (i) sells the agent only partial information, (ii) induces the socially efficient stopping rule, and (iii) extracts the full surplus. However, introducing an additional, free source of information can lead to inefficiency in equilibrium.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/736765
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/736765
Y2  - 2026/04/24
