T1  - Persuasion and Information Aggregation in                         Elections
AU  - Heese, Carl
AU  - Lauermann, Stephan
Y1  - 2025/05/27
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/736767
DO  - 10.1086/736767
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3305
EP  - 3348
VL  - 133
IS  - 10
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper studies a large majority election with voters who have heterogeneous private preferences and exogenous private information about an unknown state of the world. We show that a Bayesian persuader can achieve any state-contingent outcome in some equilibrium by providing additional information. In this setting, without the persuader?s additional information, a version of the Condorcet jury theorem holds, in the sense that outcomes of large elections satisfy full-information equivalence. Persuasion does not require detailed knowledge of the voters? private information, preferences, or the voting rule. It also requires almost no commitment power on the part of the persuader.
AB  - This paper studies a large majority election with voters who have heterogeneous private preferences and exogenous private information about an unknown state of the world. We show that a Bayesian persuader can achieve any state-contingent outcome in some equilibrium by providing additional information. In this setting, without the persuader?s additional information, a version of the Condorcet jury theorem holds, in the sense that outcomes of large elections satisfy full-information equivalence. Persuasion does not require detailed knowledge of the voters? private information, preferences, or the voting rule. It also requires almost no commitment power on the part of the persuader.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/736767
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/736767
Y2  - 2026/04/24
